<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2001-07-24.11.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-01/wa0724.htm#9">Water Supply</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2001-07-24.11.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80245" speakername="Mr Jamie Stone (Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross) (LD)" spid="S1W-16579" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-01/wa0724.htm#QuestionText">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive <a name="QuestionText">whether the Aluminium Sulphate Concentrations (nmg/l) in the potable water supply from the Tomich water treatment plant in Invergordon exceeded the limit allowed in potable water at any time during June 2001; if so, by how much, what the maximum concentration was of any discharge and how much entered the public water supply.</a></p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2001-07-24.11.r0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80155" speakername="Ross Finnie" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-01/wa0724.htm#QuestionText">

  <p>The maximum recorded level of aluminium in samples taken from the Tain regional water supply zone in June was 249 micrograms per litre. This is a breach of the standard set in Scottish drinking water regulations which is 200 micrograms per litre, but is highly unlikely to be of any significant public health concern. This single small excess over the standard followed a compressor failure on 7 June. The restoration of water supplies led to a short-term disturbance of accumulated material within the distribution system.</p>

</reply>
